From bdf778e99f1efab2d859362f9f0012758651fa6c Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: ws63-rs <noreply@anthropic.com>
Date: Fri, 5 Jun 2026 14:11:50 +0800
Subject: [PATCH] target/riscv: fix RV32 mcycleh/minstreth PMU read (upstream
 v11 regression)
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

QEMU v11.0's riscv_pmu_read_ctr() (target/riscv/csr.c) extract64()s the high/low
slice of ctr_prev/ctr_val for an RV32 fixed counter, but reads the fixed-counter
value (riscv_pmu_ctr_get_fixed_counters_val) WITHOUT slicing — so the upper-half
read (mcycleh / minstreth) returns the low 32 bits of the 64-bit counter
(cpu_get_host_ticks()) instead of the high 32 bits. The value then changes on
every read, so firmware doing the standard atomic 64-bit read
  csrr hi, mcycleh; csrr lo, mcycle; csrr hi2, mcycleh; bne hi, hi2, retry
never converges and spins forever (observed: ws63-rs rf_port_demo hangs after
osal_kmalloc on v11; passes on v9.2.4/v10.0.0/v10.2.3, which sliced the fixed
value internally via the pre-v11 get_fixed_counters_val(..., upper_half)).

Fix: slice the fixed-counter value with the same extract64(.., start, length)
applied to ctr_prev/ctr_val. Restores correct mcycleh/minstreth on RV32.

Co-Authored-By: Claude Opus 4.8 <noreply@anthropic.com>
---
 target/riscv/csr.c | 4 ++--
 1 file changed, 2 insertions(+), 2 deletions(-)

diff --git a/target/riscv/csr.c b/target/riscv/csr.c
index 29dd596..848b02c 100644
--- a/target/riscv/csr.c
+++ b/target/riscv/csr.c
@@ -1389,8 +1389,8 @@ RISCVException riscv_pmu_read_ctr(CPURISCVState *env, target_ulong *val,
      */
     if (riscv_pmu_ctr_monitor_cycles(env, ctr_idx) ||
         riscv_pmu_ctr_monitor_instructions(env, ctr_idx)) {
-        *val = riscv_pmu_ctr_get_fixed_counters_val(env, ctr_idx) -
-                                                    ctr_prev + ctr_val;
+        *val = extract64(riscv_pmu_ctr_get_fixed_counters_val(env, ctr_idx),
+                         start, length) - ctr_prev + ctr_val;
     } else {
         *val = ctr_val;
     }
-- 
